entries.meaning: simple past tense and past participle of win

description: From Old English wunian, from Proto-Germanic *wunāną, from Proto-Indo-European *wenh₁- (“to wish, love”). Cognate with Dutch wonen, German wohnen.

verbs.description: won (third-person singular simple present wons, present participle wonning, simple past and past participle wonned)

entries.meaning: (archaic or obsolete, regional) To live, remain.
examples: I long'd to leave this wand'ring pilgrimage, / And in my native soil again to won.

entries.meaning: (archaic or obsolete, regional) To be accustomed to do something.

description: Borrowed from Korean 원 (圓, won), from Sinitic 圓／圆 (yuán, “circle” > “round coin”) referring to the piece of eight. Doublet of yuan and yen.

entries.meaning: The currency of Korea, worth 100 jun in North Korea and 100 jeon in South Korea.
